<div class="grid-column-container" id="post-46981">
	<div class="main-content">
		<div class="recipe-body">
  			<p><strong>A super flavorful, very authentic chicken pho that takes about 3 hours to make.</strong></p>
<p>This is my personal chicken pho recipe that I&#8217;ve been refining for the past 10 years. It&#8217;s different (and less accessible) than the <a href="https://amzn.to/3vtzHXZ">easier one in our cookbook.</a> I&#8217;m finally putting it up because Steph wanted to be able to make it rather than ask me to do so every time she craved chicken pho.</p>
<p>It&#8217;s aromatic, refreshing, light, and deeply satisfying. It takes a little bit of effort but I think it&#8217;s worth it. You might even skip the restaurants after this one.</p>
<h2 data-heading="A personal recipe">A personal recipe</h2>
<p>This is going to be an old school blog post.</p>
<p>Back in the early 2010s when blogging was a bigger thing, before tiktok, everyone seemed to be doing over-the-top giant multi-hour project recipes. Blogging went from headlines like <em>72-hour Slow Roasted Beef Rib Pho with Homemade Rice Noodles</em> to <em>Easy Best 15 Minute Pho</em>. Steph and I are no less guilty of this, but I feel like we lost something along the way. This post is definitely not designed to rank high on search. Instead, it&#8217;s the most delicious pho recipe that I know how to make.</p>
<p><picture class="alignnone size-full wp-image-46989 sp-no-webp"><source data-lazy-srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6293.webp 1450w,https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6293-480x600.webp 480w,https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6293-819x1024.webp 819w,https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6293-1229x1536.webp 1229w" sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px" type="image/webp"><source data-lazy-srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6293.jpg 1450w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6293-480x600.jpg 480w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6293-819x1024.jpg 819w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6293-1229x1536.jpg 1229w" sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px" type="image/jpeg"><img src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%201450%201812'%3E%3C/svg%3E" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-46989 sp-no-webp" alt="Chicken Pho Recipe | www.iamafoodblog.com" height="1812" width="1450" data-lazy-srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6293.jpg 1450w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6293-480x600.jpg 480w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6293-819x1024.jpg 819w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6293-1229x1536.jpg 1229w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px" data-lazy-src="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6293.jpg"><noscript><img src="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6293.jpg" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-46989 sp-no-webp" alt="Chicken Pho Recipe | www.iamafoodblog.com" height="1812" width="1450" srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6293.jpg 1450w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6293-480x600.jpg 480w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6293-819x1024.jpg 819w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6293-1229x1536.jpg 1229w" sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px"></noscript></picture></p>
<h2 data-heading="What is chicken pho (phá»Ÿ gÃ )">What is chicken pho (phá»Ÿ gÃ )</h2>
<p>Chicken pho is a less well known though no less authentic version of pho. It has roughly the same flavor profile, but is lighter, healthier, and faster and cheaper to make. If you love pho, you owe it to yourself to try a great chicken pho. It&#8217;s like steak vs fried chicken, both are equally delicious.</p>
<h2 data-heading="Equipment">Equipment</h2>
<p>For this recipe the following equipment isn&#8217;t strictly needed but guarantees an easy experience:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>A large stockpot.</strong> You&#8217;ll need a pot that&#8217;s large enough to hold a whole broken down chicken plus an onion and ginger. Most of the stockpots that come in those 7 piece sets are just large enough, but the bigger the better.</li>
<li><strong>A kitchen torch.</strong> I use a full-on blowtorch. You can toast the spices some other way (like in a cast iron pan) but it won&#8217;t be as smoky and delicious.</li>
<li><strong>Tongs.</strong> We&#8217;ll be moving a lot of chicken around, and tongs are the best cooking utensils for this. If you have metal tipped ones, you can use them to debone the chicken after it&#8217;s been cooked rather than a knife and fork.</li>
<li><strong>2 large mixing bowls.</strong> I use these to transfer the chicken, debone the chicken, weigh the noodles, etc.</li>
<li><strong>Sieve and 4qt container.</strong> To strain the soup. <a href="https://amzn.to/4sThmim">We own and love these 4qt cambros</a> (shown below) that you can get from any restaurant supply store or <a href="https://amzn.to/4sThmim">online</a>. They&#8217;re useful for soup making, of course, but also storing large amounts of leftovers and general storage. Steph uses a larger 10qt one just for her instant noodle library.</li>
<li><strong>Noodle Bowls and Chopsticks.</strong> To serve and eat, more on that below.</li>
</ul>
<p><picture class="alignnone size-full wp-image-46983 sp-no-webp"><source data-lazy-srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6260.webp 1450w,https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6260-600x401.webp 600w,https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6260-1024x684.webp 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px" type="image/webp"><source data-lazy-srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6260.jpg 1450w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6260-600x401.jpg 600w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6260-1024x684.jpg 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px" type="image/jpeg"><img src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%201450%20968'%3E%3C/svg%3E" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-46983 sp-no-webp" alt="4qt Cambro | www.iamafoodblog.com" height="968" width="1450" data-lazy-srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6260.jpg 1450w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6260-600x401.jpg 600w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6260-1024x684.jpg 1024w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px" data-lazy-src="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6260.jpg"><noscript><img src="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6260.jpg" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-46983 sp-no-webp" alt="4qt Cambro | www.iamafoodblog.com" height="968" width="1450" srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6260.jpg 1450w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6260-600x401.jpg 600w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6260-1024x684.jpg 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px"></noscript></picture></p>
<h2 data-heading="How to make chicken pho">How to make chicken pho</h2>
<p>Although I&#8217;m talking up how difficult this recipe is, it&#8217;s not really that complicated. Here&#8217;s how you make chicken pho:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Char your aromatics.</strong> Char your onion and ginger for about 10 seconds. I use a blowtorch, but a small kitchen torch will work too. Transfer to your large stockpot. Pro tip: leave the hood fan <strong>off</strong> because this process creates some ash and the hood fan sucks it right into the filter if you have it on.</li>
<li><strong>Briefly char your spices.</strong> Just about a second is enough. Then transfer to a tea bag if you have one and add to the stockpot</li>
<li><strong>Add chicken and cover with water.</strong> Bring to a boil. Note the time that the soup has come to a boil.</li>
<li><strong>Remove the chicken and cool.</strong> About 25 minutes after the soup boils, remove the chicken and allow to cool. Keep the soup at a low simmer and add water if needed.</li>
<li><strong>Debone the chicken.</strong> About 15 minutes later the chicken will have cooled enough to handle. Roughly remove the meat from the bones. You don&#8217;t need to work too hard on this, any meat left over just helps flavor the soup. Transfer the meat to a container, cover, and refrigerate.</li>
<li><strong>Simmer the soup.</strong> Add the bones back to the soup and simmer for 30 mins to 2 hours. The longer the better, obviously.</li>
<li><strong>Strain the soup.</strong> I&#8217;ve found that removing the bones and larger pieces makes straining easier.</li>
<li><strong>Season the soup.</strong> This is a pretty personal thing but I&#8217;ve included my suggestions in the recipe.</li>
<li><strong>Build your bowls and enjoy.</strong> Instructions below.</li>
</ol>
<p><picture class="alignnone size-full wp-image-47005 sp-no-webp"><source data-lazy-srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6193.webp 1450w,https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6193-600x401.webp 600w,https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6193-1024x684.webp 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px" type="image/webp"><source data-lazy-srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6193.jpg 1450w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6193-600x401.jpg 600w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6193-1024x684.jpg 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px" type="image/jpeg"><img src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%201450%20968'%3E%3C/svg%3E" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-47005 sp-no-webp" alt="charring pho spices | www.iamafoodblog.com" height="968" width="1450" data-lazy-srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6193.jpg 1450w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6193-600x401.jpg 600w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6193-1024x684.jpg 1024w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px" data-lazy-src="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6193.jpg"><noscript><img src="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6193.jpg" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-47005 sp-no-webp" alt="charring pho spices | www.iamafoodblog.com" height="968" width="1450" srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6193.jpg 1450w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6193-600x401.jpg 600w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6193-1024x684.jpg 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px"></noscript></picture></p>
<h2 data-heading="How to serve chicken pho">How to serve chicken pho</h2>
<p>Serving any noodle soup so that everything is hot and ready at the same time (and not soggy) is an art form. Pho is one of the easiest noodles in this respect because the noodles are better the longer they sit out, and the soup goes in last. This is my method:</p>
<ol>
<li>Optional: warm the bowls</li>
<li><strong>Bring the soup to a low simmer</strong> in one pot and bring up a large amount of boiling water in another large pot.</li>
<li><strong>Blanch the noodles</strong> according to the instructions on the package. For fresh noodles you dip it in boiling water for 1-2 seconds and drain immediately. For dry noodles it can be as long as 5 minutes depending on the thickness of the noodles, but usually 1-2 minutes.</li>
<li><strong>Drain and rinse the noodles</strong> in a mesh sieve. Unlike pasta, rinsing the noodles removes the residual starch and gives you a cleaner end product.</li>
<li><strong>Divide the noodles.</strong> If you are making more than 2 bowls at a time, it&#8217;s worth it to weigh and divide the noodles in a (tared) large mixing bowl. Let the noodles rest in the bowls. They&#8217;ll dry out a bit and when you add the soup they absorb a little bit of the soup and become tastier.</li>
<li><strong>Warm the chicken</strong> in the soup and divide between the bowls.</li>
<li><strong>Set up your garnishes</strong>, dips, chopsticks, spoons, drinks etc at the table.</li>
<li><strong>When everyone is ready to eat</strong>, add enough soup to the bowls to cover and carefully bring them to the table. You can optionally bring the whole pot to the table and ladle it there, which is useful in case extra soup is needed.</li>
</ol>
<p><picture class="alignnone size-full wp-image-46993 sp-no-webp"><source data-lazy-srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6286.webp 1450w,https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6286-600x401.webp 600w,https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6286-1024x684.webp 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px" type="image/webp"><source data-lazy-srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6286.jpg 1450w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6286-600x401.jpg 600w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6286-1024x684.jpg 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px" type="image/jpeg"><img src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%201450%20968'%3E%3C/svg%3E" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-46993 sp-no-webp" alt="Chicken Pho Recipe | www.iamafoodblog.com" height="968" width="1450" data-lazy-srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6286.jpg 1450w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6286-600x401.jpg 600w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6286-1024x684.jpg 1024w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px" data-lazy-src="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6286.jpg"><noscript><img src="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6286.jpg" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-46993 sp-no-webp" alt="Chicken Pho Recipe | www.iamafoodblog.com" height="968" width="1450" srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6286.jpg 1450w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6286-600x401.jpg 600w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6286-1024x684.jpg 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px"></noscript></picture></p>
<h2 data-heading="Ingredients">Chicken pho ingredients</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Chicken.</strong> This recipe was originally made to use up exactly one whole chicken. Back in the day, I would break down a whole chicken. These days, I&#8217;d rather spend a few extra dollars and buy chicken parts. My current perfect mix is 4 drumsticks, 4 thighs, and a bone-in skin-on chicken breast.</li>
<li><strong>Spices.</strong> You need about 6 spices to make this recipe, more on that below.</li>
<li><strong>Aromatics.</strong> I whittled the list down to just 1 onion and some ginger. A lot of other people will add shallots, the whites of green onions, even carrots and celery. I don&#8217;t personally feel like this is necessary but you could, if you like.</li>
<li><strong>Seasoning.</strong> For Vietnamese recipes, this is sugar, fish sauce, salt, and MSG. The MSG is optional but I personally love it for authenticity reasons. Much has been said lately about MSG and racism (all true) but I make the MSG is optional for another reason: if you don&#8217;t already use it, it&#8217;s hard to find it in a small amount. If you run into the <a href="https://amzn.to/4tAAGSW">cute MSG panda</a> though, I&#8217;d recommend getting that.</li>
<li><strong>Noodles.</strong> More on pho noodles below.</li>
<li><strong>Garnishes.</strong> Skippable but recommended. You can omit the traditional sriracha and hoisin for this one as well.</li>
</ul>
<p><picture class="alignnone size-full wp-image-46985 sp-no-webp"><source data-lazy-srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6304.webp 1450w,https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6304-600x401.webp 600w,https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6304-1024x684.webp 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px" type="image/webp"><source data-lazy-srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6304.jpg 1450w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6304-600x401.jpg 600w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6304-1024x684.jpg 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px" type="image/jpeg"><img src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%201450%20968'%3E%3C/svg%3E" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-46985 sp-no-webp" alt="MSG Panda | www.iamafoodblog.com" height="968" width="1450" data-lazy-srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6304.jpg 1450w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6304-600x401.jpg 600w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6304-1024x684.jpg 1024w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px" data-lazy-src="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6304.jpg"><noscript><img src="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6304.jpg" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-46985 sp-no-webp" alt="MSG Panda | www.iamafoodblog.com" height="968" width="1450" srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6304.jpg 1450w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6304-600x401.jpg 600w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6304-1024x684.jpg 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px"></noscript></picture></p>
<h2 data-heading="Discarding the chicken for the lazy">Discarding the chicken</h2>
<p>This recipe specifies removing the chicken 30 minutes in, harvesting the meat, and then transferring the bones back in. This is admittedly a labor-intensive step.</p>
<p>If you are super lazy and rich, you could in theory just leave all the chicken in, and then in the last 30 minutes drop in a few boneless skinless chicken breasts for serving, and discard the rest. For me, that&#8217;s a bit too much of a waste to consider doing.</p>
<p>A good middle ground would be buying chicken carcasses, which you can sometimes get from an Asian grocery store and definitely from any decent butcher. Then afterwards, drop in the chicken breasts as above.</p>
<p>Some chefs like Thomas Keller and Ivan Ramen straight up tell you in their cookbooks to boil a whole chicken for a couple of hours and discard. My Vietnamese sensibilities could never, though.</p>
<p><picture class="alignnone size-full wp-image-47004 sp-no-webp"><source data-lazy-srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6226.webp 1450w,https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6226-600x401.webp 600w,https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6226-1024x684.webp 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px" type="image/webp"><source data-lazy-srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6226.jpg 1450w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6226-600x401.jpg 600w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6226-1024x684.jpg 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px" type="image/jpeg"><img src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%201450%20968'%3E%3C/svg%3E" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-47004 sp-no-webp" alt="Deboned cooked chicken | www.iamafoodblog.com" height="968" width="1450" data-lazy-srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6226.jpg 1450w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6226-600x401.jpg 600w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6226-1024x684.jpg 1024w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px" data-lazy-src="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6226.jpg"><noscript><img src="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6226.jpg" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-47004 sp-no-webp" alt="Deboned cooked chicken | www.iamafoodblog.com" height="968" width="1450" srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6226.jpg 1450w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6226-600x401.jpg 600w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6226-1024x684.jpg 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px"></noscript></picture></p>
<h2 data-heading="The spice pack">The spice pack</h2>
<p>Getting the spices are generally the hardest part of making pho at home. Pho spices are intensely personal. In some cities there are (or were) pho masters who went around to all the different pho restaurants selling custom spice mixes so that the restauranteurs could guarantee quality and uniqueness. The spices are what makes pho special for me. A lot of pho recipes online seem to skip the spices entirely, I wouldn&#8217;t trust those recipes.</p>
<p>On the other hand, many pho recipes can contain up to a dozen spices. Over the years I&#8217;ve whittled down my spice pack to just 6 spices: star anise, cinnamon, coriander, white pepper, cloves, and cardamom. All of these spices are ideally whole, not ground. <a href="https://amzn.to/4t58TsQ">Whole star anise in particular can be hard to find outside of Asian grocery stores and online.</a></p>
<p><picture class="alignnone size-full wp-image-47006 sp-no-webp"><source data-lazy-srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6203.webp 1450w,https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6203-600x401.webp 600w,https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6203-1024x684.webp 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px" type="image/webp"><source data-lazy-srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6203.jpg 1450w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6203-600x401.jpg 600w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6203-1024x684.jpg 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px" type="image/jpeg"><img src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%201450%20968'%3E%3C/svg%3E" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-47006 sp-no-webp" alt="Charred aromatics for pho | www.iamafoodblog.com" height="968" width="1450" data-lazy-srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6203.jpg 1450w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6203-600x401.jpg 600w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6203-1024x684.jpg 1024w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px" data-lazy-src="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6203.jpg"><noscript><img src="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6203.jpg" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-47006 sp-no-webp" alt="Charred aromatics for pho | www.iamafoodblog.com" height="968" width="1450" srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6203.jpg 1450w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6203-600x401.jpg 600w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6203-1024x684.jpg 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px"></noscript></picture></p>
<h2 data-heading="Charring">Charring</h2>
<p>The word pho is often said to come from the French phrase <em>pot au feu</em> and the reason was the charring of the aromatics and spices. If you don&#8217;t have a flame source, you can skip this step but it worth chasing down at least <a href="https://amzn.to/4eJ3h3D">a cheap kitchen torch</a>. <a href="https://amzn.to/4sToLOG">These butane toppers are also usually about $10</a> and the butane gas itself is about $1.50 a can.</p>
<p>For me, I pair the classic bernzomatic TS-8000 that&#8217;s found in restaurant kitchens across the world with a green coleman propane can for a less industrial/plumbing look. They don&#8217;t take up much room when stored separately. We use it more often than you&#8217;d think, including when camping to easily start a campfire. The bernzomatic brand is an industry standard and priced as such, but there are <a href="https://amzn.to/4vMHpuo">identical looking clones online for cheap</a>, though I can&#8217;t vouch for how good they are.</p>
<p><picture class="alignnone size-full wp-image-46986 sp-no-webp"><source data-lazy-srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6305.webp 1450w,https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6305-480x600.webp 480w,https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6305-819x1024.webp 819w,https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6305-1229x1536.webp 1229w" sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px" type="image/webp"><source data-lazy-srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6305.jpg 1450w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6305-480x600.jpg 480w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6305-819x1024.jpg 819w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6305-1229x1536.jpg 1229w" sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px" type="image/jpeg"><img src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%201450%201812'%3E%3C/svg%3E" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-46986 sp-no-webp" alt="TS8000 torch | www.iamafoodblog.com" height="1812" width="1450" data-lazy-srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6305.jpg 1450w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6305-480x600.jpg 480w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6305-819x1024.jpg 819w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6305-1229x1536.jpg 1229w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px" data-lazy-src="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6305.jpg"><noscript><img src="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6305.jpg" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-46986 sp-no-webp" alt="TS8000 torch | www.iamafoodblog.com" height="1812" width="1450" srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6305.jpg 1450w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6305-480x600.jpg 480w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6305-819x1024.jpg 819w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6305-1229x1536.jpg 1229w" sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px"></noscript></picture></p>
<h2 data-heading="Garnishes">Garnishes</h2>
<p>Of anything in this recipe that you can skip, I&#8217;d say the garnishes are the most optional. Pho is traditionally served with lime, cilantro, thai basil, and chilies. It&#8217;s up to you if you want to go with these or not, when we&#8217;re lazy we often skip them all. The soup is great as is.</p>
<h2 data-heading="Fish sauce">Fish sauce</h2>
<p>If you don&#8217;t intend to make the dipping sauce and you don&#8217;t want to buy fish sauce, this recipe works without it. Fish sauce adds a depth of flavor that you can&#8217;t get with just salt. However, many a Vietnamese household makes pho with just salt for a cleaner, more chicken forward taste.</p>
<p>If you want to skip the fish sauce, just add the equivalent amount of salt to replace it (or as much/as little as your taste prefers).</p>
<p>For this recipe (and all seasoning purposes) I prefer a cheaper brand like <a href="https://amzn.to/4cMEnxu">Golden Boy</a> over something like <a href="https://amzn.to/4mZRz6X">Red Boat</a>. Unless you have it already, a high end fish sauce here would be a waste of money, like using high end olive oil to fry.</p>
<p><picture class="alignnone size-full wp-image-47010 sp-no-webp"><source data-lazy-srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6242.webp 1450w,https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6242-600x401.webp 600w,https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6242-1024x684.webp 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px" type="image/webp"><source data-lazy-srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6242.jpg 1450w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6242-600x401.jpg 600w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6242-1024x684.jpg 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px" type="image/jpeg"><img src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%201450%20968'%3E%3C/svg%3E" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-47010 sp-no-webp" alt="Ginger fish sauce | www.iamafoodblog.com" height="968" width="1450" data-lazy-srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6242.jpg 1450w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6242-600x401.jpg 600w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6242-1024x684.jpg 1024w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px" data-lazy-src="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6242.jpg"><noscript><img src="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6242.jpg" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-47010 sp-no-webp" alt="Ginger fish sauce | www.iamafoodblog.com" height="968" width="1450" srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6242.jpg 1450w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6242-600x401.jpg 600w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6242-1024x684.jpg 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px"></noscript></picture></p>
<h2 data-heading="Dipping sauce">Dipping sauce</h2>
<p>This recipe comes with a ginger fish sauce-based dipping sauce. I think it really makes the dish. Even though we traditionally only use ginger fish sauce with poultry, I love it so much we use it anywhere a fish sauce dipping sauce is called for.</p>
<p>The ginger isn&#8217;t an exact measurement because who weighs ginger? Generally speaking, err on the side of more ginger than you&#8217;d expect. How much I use is illustrated in these two before/after photos.</p>
<p><picture class="alignnone size-full wp-image-47001 sp-no-webp"><source data-lazy-srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6248.webp 1450w,https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6248-600x401.webp 600w,https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6248-1024x684.webp 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px" type="image/webp"><source data-lazy-srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6248.jpg 1450w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6248-600x401.jpg 600w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6248-1024x684.jpg 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px" type="image/jpeg"><img src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%201450%20968'%3E%3C/svg%3E" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-47001 sp-no-webp" alt="Ginger fish sauce | www.iamafoodblog.com" height="968" width="1450" data-lazy-srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6248.jpg 1450w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6248-600x401.jpg 600w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6248-1024x684.jpg 1024w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px" data-lazy-src="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6248.jpg"><noscript><img src="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6248.jpg" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-47001 sp-no-webp" alt="Ginger fish sauce | www.iamafoodblog.com" height="968" width="1450" srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6248.jpg 1450w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6248-600x401.jpg 600w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6248-1024x684.jpg 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px"></noscript></picture></p>
<h2 data-heading="Pho noodles">Pho noodles</h2>
<p>The best kind of pho noodles you can buy are fresh rice noodles. They&#8217;re usually stored in the fridge at your local Asian grocery store near the tofu. These noodles are what your local pho restaurant uses and their texture is great.</p>
<p>You can also get dried rice stick noodles in the Asian aisle at any major grocery store. Sometimes it&#8217;s called pad thai noodles. Their texture isn&#8217;t as good but it works. We&#8217;ve used fettuccine in a pinch before.</p>
<p><picture class="alignnone size-full wp-image-46984 sp-no-webp"><source data-lazy-srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6301.webp 1450w,https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6301-600x401.webp 600w,https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6301-1024x684.webp 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px" type="image/webp"><source data-lazy-srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6301.jpg 1450w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6301-600x401.jpg 600w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6301-1024x684.jpg 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px" type="image/jpeg"><img src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%201450%20968'%3E%3C/svg%3E" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-46984 sp-no-webp" alt="Fresh pho noodles | www.iamafoodblog.com" height="968" width="1450" data-lazy-srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6301.jpg 1450w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6301-600x401.jpg 600w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6301-1024x684.jpg 1024w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px" data-lazy-src="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6301.jpg"><noscript><img src="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6301.jpg" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-46984 sp-no-webp" alt="Fresh pho noodles | www.iamafoodblog.com" height="968" width="1450" srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6301.jpg 1450w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6301-600x401.jpg 600w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6301-1024x684.jpg 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px"></noscript></picture></p>
<h2 data-heading="Noodle bowls">Noodle bowls</h2>
<p>The hardest thing about making pho in a non Asian household/kitchen is that most people don&#8217;t have noodle bowls.</p>
<p>The ideal noodle bowl is at least 6&#8243; wide and 5&#8243; high. Our collection has bowls from East Fork, Kinto, and Farmhouse Pottery, as well as tons of other random ones we picked up over the years. You can also get some great basic bowls from your local Asian grocery store or online. Bonus, they make great cereal bowls (and are often what they&#8217;re marketed as).</p>
<p>When I was younger and couldn&#8217;t afford noodle bowls, I ate out of mixing bowls. That&#8217;s what we still do when we eat pho in airbnbs, and it works.</p>
<p><picture class="alignnone size-full wp-image-46982 sp-no-webp"><source data-lazy-srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6309.webp 1450w,https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6309-600x401.webp 600w,https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6309-1024x684.webp 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px" type="image/webp"><source data-lazy-srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6309.jpg 1450w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6309-600x401.jpg 600w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6309-1024x684.jpg 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px" type="image/jpeg"><img src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%201450%20968'%3E%3C/svg%3E" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-46982 sp-no-webp" alt="Noodle Bowls | www.iamafoodblog.com" height="968" width="1450" data-lazy-srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6309.jpg 1450w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6309-600x401.jpg 600w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6309-1024x684.jpg 1024w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px" data-lazy-src="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6309.jpg"><noscript><img src="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6309.jpg" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-46982 sp-no-webp" alt="Noodle Bowls | www.iamafoodblog.com" height="968" width="1450" srcset="https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6309.jpg 1450w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6309-600x401.jpg 600w, https://iamafoodblog.b-cdn.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/chicken-pho-6309-1024x684.jpg 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 1450px) 100vw, 1450px"></noscript></picture></p>
<h2 data-heading="Asian supermarkets">Asian supermarkets</h2>
<p>Throughout this post I mentioned the Asian supermarket a lot, and that&#8217;s because the best place to stock up on supplies for pho is here. You&#8217;ll get cheaper meat, reasonably priced whole spices, a wider selection of fish sauce, and fresh noodles quickly and easily. You can still cobble this recipe together if the only place in your town is a Ralphs or Kroger. However, if you have a 99 ranch or T&amp;T or similar near you, the experience is just so much better.</p>
